So as you can see in my core project I do not bother much with the LifeCycle, I just let libGDX do the job for me.

In my IOSLauncher I have tried the following pieces of code:

```
@Override
    public void didBecomeActive(UIApplication application) {
        super.didBecomeActive(application);
        FBSDKAppEvents.activateApp();
        Gdx.app.getApplicationListener().render();
    }

    @Override
    public void willResignActive(UIApplication application) {
        super.willResignActive(application);
        Gdx.app.getApplicationListener().pause();
        Gdx.gl.glFlush();
        application
    }

    @Override
    public void willTerminate(UIApplication application) {
        super.willTerminate(application);
        Gdx.app.debug("IOSApplication", "disposed");
        Gdx.gl.glFlush();
        Gdx.app.getApplicationListener().dispose();
    }

    @Override
    public void didEnterBackground(UIApplication application) {
        super.didEnterBackground(application);
        Gdx.gl.glFlush();
        Gdx.app.log("did", "ENTER BACKGROUND");
    }

    @Override
    public void willEnterForeground(UIApplication application) {
        super.willEnterForeground(application);
        Gdx.app.log("WILL ENTER FOREGROUND", "");
        Gdx.app.getApplicationListener().resume();
    }
```

The strange thing is that even the messages are not shown in my tab, so these methods are never even called. 

I use RoboVM 1.14, I believe that is the latest version.

Googling the issue I found that many have encountered the same problem, however, I have spent about 2 weeks trying to find a solution and I still have not found it + my RoboVM license is ending in a couple of days......

